Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Pour 300ml cold @salted water{300%ml} into a #medium pot{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}.

Stir in the @jasmine rice{150%g} and bring to the boil.

Once boiling, lower the heat to medium, cover and cook for ~{12%minutes}.

Remove the #pot{} from the heat. Keep covered for another ~{12%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, trim and thinly slice the @radish{125%g}.

Pop the radish into a #small bowl{} along with the @red wine vinegar{1%sachet}, @sugar{1%tsp} and @salt{1/4%tsp}.

Mix together and set aside. Stir frequently.

Peel and grate the @ginger{1}.

Use a #teaspoon{} to easily scrape away the peel.

Roughly chop the @mushrooms{150%g}.

Place a #pan{} over high heat with the @sesame oil{20%ml}.

Once hot, add the mushrooms and ginger.

Cook until charred, shifting occasionally, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Meanwhile, drain and rinse the @lentils{1%pack} in a #sieve{}.

Reduce the heat of the pan to medium-high.

Add half the @gochujang paste{1%sachet}, @soy sauce{1%sachet}, @coconut milk{1%pack}, lentils, and @sugar{1/2%tsp} to the pan.

Cover and simmer for ~{8-10%minutes}.

Season to taste with @salt{to taste}, @pepper{to taste} and @sugar{to taste}. Add a splash of @water{to taste} if the lentils are too dry.

> TIP: You might want to add the gochujang a little at a time, tasting as you go—it's spicy!

Meanwhile, strip the leafy part of the @kale{80%g} from the stem and chop into bite-sized pieces. Discard the stems (they're too tough to eat).

Spread the kale out on a lined #baking tray{}.

Toss with @salt{to taste}, @pepper{to taste} and a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

When the oven is hot, bake on the middle shelf until crispy, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Meanwhile, in a small bowl, mix the @aioli{1%sachet} with the remaining gochujang.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and divide between bowls.

Arrange the pickled radish, roasted kale, spicy lentils and mushrooms alongside.

Finish with a drizzle of the gochujang aioli.